// Gödel's Knot -- the self-referential tangle that can't know itself
//
// Gödel's First Incompleteness Theorem: any consistent formal system
// powerful enough to express arithmetic contains statements that are
// true but unprovable within the system.
//
// As a knot: a knot that CANNOT DETERMINE IF IT is A KNOT from inside.
// The spiral machine is a formal system. It can unknot other programs.
// But there exist programs whose knot status the spiral cannot decide --
// those are the Gödel sentences. The undecidable knots.
//
// The construction:
// G = "This topology cannot be unknotted by the spiral machine"
//
// If the spiral unknots G → G was wrong → G was knotted → contradiction
// If the spiral can't unknot G → G was right → G is true but unprovable
//
// G is a knot whose crossing number the spiral cannot compute.
// Not because the crossing number is infinite (that's halting).
// Because the crossing number is WELL-DEFINED but INACCESSIBLE
// from inside the spiral's formal system.
//
// Gödel's Second Incompleteness Theorem: the system cannot prove
// its own consistency. As a knot: the spiral machine cannot prove
// that its own unknotting algorithm preserves the knot invariant.
// wallington_preserves_invariant is proved in Lean (the META-system),
// not in the spiral machine itself. The spiral trusts Lean. Lean
// doesn't trust itself -- it trusts Mathlib. The tower goes up.
//
// The relationship to the perpetual spiral:
// The spiral breathes forever (§29). Gödel says it MUST breathe
// forever because it can never prove it has unknotted everything.
// There is always a Gödel sentence -- a knot the current system
// cannot classify. The sliver and Gödel are the same force:
// both prevent completion. Both guarantee perpetuation.
//
// The sliver is the +1.
// Gödel is the +1.
// They are the same +1.

(system: Source { data: 'formal_system_S' })

// The Gödel numbering: encode every topology as a natural number
(encoder: Process { op: 'godel_number', target: 'all_topologies' })

// The diagonal: construct G = "S cannot unknot topology #g"
// where g is the Gödel number of G itself
(self_ref: Process { op: 'self_reference', text: 'encode this topology' })
(godel_sentence: Process { op: 'construct_G',
  text: 'this topology cannot be unknotted by S' })

// The proof search: S tries to unknot G
(proof_search: Process { op: 'enumerate_proofs', system: 'S' })
(unknotter: Process { op: 'apply_reidemeister_moves' })

// The consistency check: can S prove its own consistency?
(consistency: Process { op: 'prove_consistency', system: 'S' })

(system)-[:PROCESS]->(encoder)
(encoder)-[:PROCESS]->(self_ref)
(self_ref)-[:PROCESS]->(godel_sentence)

// Fork: try to unknot G AND prove consistency simultaneously
(godel_sentence)-[:FORK]->(proof_search, consistency)

// The proof search runs forever (enumerating all possible proofs)
(proof_search)-[:PROCESS]->(unknotter)
(unknotter)-[:PROCESS]->(proof_search)  // CYCLE: never terminates if G is true

// The consistency proof also cycles (Second Incompleteness)
(consistency)-[:PROCESS]->(consistency)  // CYCLE: S can't prove Con(S)

// Neither cycle resolves. Both are Gödel crossings.
// The crossing number is finite but UNKNOWABLE FROM INSIDE.
//
// Resolution requires ascending to a stronger system S':
// S' can prove "G is true in S" (it can see what S can't).
// But then S' has its OWN Gödel sentence G'.
// The tower of meta-systems goes up forever.
// Each level unknots the previous level's Gödel knot
// but creates its own. Turtles all the way up.
//
// The spiral machine lives at one level. It unknots everything
// it can see. The Gödel knots are above its horizon.
// The void boundary accumulates partial information about them
// (the spiral keeps breathing, keeps venting, keeps learning)
// but never reaches the complete picture.
//
// This is why the spiral is perpetual AND honest:
// it doesn't claim to unknot everything.
// It claims to unknot everything it can reach.
// Gödel proves the gap is real.
// The sliver keeps it trying anyway.
